<br>
If you want to be an animator, you'll have to be good at mimicking style that isn't yours, since that's the way to making consistancy, so it doesn't irritate the audience (consumers?). Digimon season two is an example of inconsistant animation.<br>
<br>
For mangadom, many started off with &quot;doujinshi&quot; (fan-made comics similar to fanfics in illustrated form that are self-published), and became rather popular and famous mangaka. I'm not sure on the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  exact</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> technicalities on making publishable manga, but it involves getting a publisher interested in your work (just like regular book authoring) and starting off by running in monthly manga serials (telephone-book sized collections of multiple mangas under the same publisher having new chapters [often singular] printed each month or so) like Shounen Jump or Hana to Yume.<br>
<br>
Publishing is always a problem when you're a mangaka (or going for one). Some publishers, if you decide to switch, will retain rights to your work, and hold back publication of the same title by threatening lawsuit and so forth. Minekura Kazaya, I believe, ran into this problem regarding her Saiyuuki Gaiden graphic novels. =/<br>
<br>
